SIMPLE: which
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Which
<hw>Which</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>pron.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>which</ets>, <ets>whilk</ets>, AS. <ets>hwilc</ets>,
<ets>hwylc</ets>, <ets>hwelc</ets>, from the root of <ets>hw⟦amac⟧</ets>
who + <ets>l⟦imac⟧c</ets> body; hence properly, of what sort or kind;
akin to OS. <ets>hwilik</ets> which, OFries. <ets>hwelik</ets>, D.
<ets>welk</ets>, G. <ets>welch</ets>, OHG. <ets>wel⟦imac⟧h</ets>,
<ets>hwel⟦imac⟧h</ets>, Icel. <ets>hv⟦imac⟧l⟦imac⟧kr</ets>, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>hvilken</ets>, Goth. <ets>hwileiks</ets>,
<ets>hw</ets><?/<ets>leiks</ets>; cf. L. <ets>qualis</ets>.
<?/<?/<?/<?/. See <er>Who</er>, and <er>Like</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Such</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of what sort or kind; what; what a; who.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>which</qex> they weren and of what degree.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A interrogative pronoun, used both substantively and
adjectively, and in direct and indirect questions, to ask for, or refer
to, an individual person or thing among several of a class; <as>as,
<ex>which</ex> man is it? <ex>which</ex> woman was it? <ex>which</ex> is
the house? he asked <ex>which</ex> route he should take; <ex>which</ex>
is best, to live or to die?</as> See the Note under <er>What</er>,
<pos>pron.</pos>, 1.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Which</qex> of you convinceth me of sin?</q> <rj><qau>John
viii. 46.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A relative pronoun, used esp. in referring to an
antecedent noun or clause, but sometimes with reference to what is
specified or implied in a sentence, or to a following noun or clause
(generally involving a reference, however, to something which has
preceded). It is used in all numbers and genders, and was formerly used
of persons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when thou fail'st -- as God forbid the hour! --⟦br⟧
Must Edward fall, <qex>which</qex> peril heaven forfend!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God . . . rested on the seventh day from all his work
<qex>which</qex> he had made.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. ii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our Father, <qex>which</qex> art in heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vi.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The temple of God is holy, <qex>which</qex> temple ye are.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Cor. iii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A compound relative or indefinite pronoun, standing
for <xex>any one which</xex>, <xex>whichever</xex>, <xex>that
which</xex>, <xex>those which</xex>, <xex>the</xex> . . .
<xex>which</xex>, and the like; <as>as, take <ex>which</ex> you
will</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>The which</xex> was formerly often used for
<xex>which</xex>. The expressions <xex>which that</xex>, <xex>which
as</xex>, were also sometimes used by way of emphasis.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do not they blaspheme that worthy name by <qex>the which</qex> ye
are called?</q> <rj><qau>James ii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Which</xex>, referring to a series of preceding
sentences, or members of a sentence, may have <xex>all</xex> joined to
it adjectively. ⟦ldquo⟧All <xex>which</xex>, as a method of a
proclamation, is very convenient.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Carlyle.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whichsoever</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Whichever</ent>⟦br⟧
